passages.text: The 2Q earnings cycle in Business & Information Services was characterized by an intensified debate over whether Gen Al could negatively disrupt certain companies in the sector. Gartner's 2Q results, which involved a miss- and- cut, ignited investor concerns that Gen Al could replace the company's IT research and insights, sending shares \(28\%\) lower as contract value growth decelerated in the quarter and was guided by management to decelerate further in the second half of the year. Gen Al concerns at Gartner spilled over to other names in the space, including CSGP, FDS, RELGB and WKLLNL. Based on takeaways from our recent 2nd annual Silicon Valley Al Field Trip, we believe sustainable moats in Business & Info Services capable of protecting from Gen Al competition include strong user sociology, i.e., having distributed users, power users and embedded workflows that make the product sticky, and proprietary data that cannot be replicated or produced by LLMs. We see Gartner - down \(49\%\) YTD - as oversold given its research and insights are proprietary and cannot be reliably or closely substituted by LLMs. We also believe SPGI is favorably leveraged to Gen Al given assistant and agentic capabilities being incorporated into its products, and its proprietary data. IRM's data center business should additionally benefit from rising Gen Al infrastructure capex to support growing inference needs as enterprise adoption of Gen Al increases.

2Q price action reflected debates over Al impact. In the CY2Q earnings cycle, investors were focused on how Business Services companies could have been disrupted by, or benefited from, growing enterprise adoption of Gen Al. Gartner represented a pivotal moment this past earnings cycle, with the share price declining \(28\%\) ir response to miss- and- cut results that investors attributed, at least in part, to GAI disintermediation, in contrast with management's explanation that the deceleration in Insights CV growth was due to reduced federal government spending and tariff impacts. Investor concerns over Gen Al also surfaced in quarterly result at HRB (down \(5\%\) ) and RHI (down \(6\%\) ), with spillover effects at CSGP, FDS

Other Business Services companies that underperformed with 2Q results missed on KPIs (KLC - 19%, IRM - 6%, HRB - 5%, CLVT - 4%), had outright revenue declines due to execution factors (BV - 6%, VSTS - 6%), did not meet investor expectations for a guidance raise (ULS - 12%, TRI - 10%, VRSK - 6%) or exhibited negative cyclical exposures (MSCI - 9%, EFX - 8%, RHI - 6%). Revenue performance driven by pricing power, transaction volumes or sticky subscriptions. CY2Q organic revenue growth in Business & Info Services ranged from \(+20\%\) y/y to \(- 7\%\) , and companies that exhibited the strongest growth trends had outsized pricing power (FICO \(+20\%\) y/y, IRM \(+9\%\) , TRU \(+9\%\) and EFX \(+8\%\) helped indirectly by FICO AUM linked revenue benefits (MSCI \(+8\%\) y/y), or growing subscription revenue streams (BFAM \(+9\%\) y/y, CTAS \(+9\%\) , VRSK \(+8\%\) ). Not surprisingly, names with revenue declines had staffing exposure (RHI \(- 7\%\) y/y, MAN \(- 4\%\) ) or worsened in their revenue turnaround due to market share loss, reduced customer discretionary spend or project delays (BV \(- 4\%\) y/y, VSTS \(- 3\%\) ). Info Services companies had average organic revenue growth of \(7.4\%\) y/y in CY2Q 2025, which accelerated from \(7.0\%\) in CY1Q, while Business Services companies had average organic revenue growth of \(2.9\%\) in CY2Q, which accelerated from \(2.2\%\) in CY1Q.

EBITDA margins mostly expanded in 2Q. EBITDA margins mostly expanded in Business & Info Services in CY2Q driven by operating leverage, cost efficiencies and pricing flow- through. Nearly all Info Services delivered y/y EBITDA margin expansion in the quarter, with only a few exceptions (CLVT, FDS, TRU) related to low revenue growth, elevated investment spend or M&A. Info Services companies on average delivered \(42.1\%\) EBITDA margins in CY2Q with average y/y margin expansion of 110 bps. Business Services companies saw more instances of y/y EBITDA margin contraction (BCO, CTAS, HRB, KLC, MAN, RHI, ROL, VSTS) due to increased investment spend or negative operating leverage from revenue declines. Business Services companies on average delivered \(21.1\%\) EBITDA margins in CY2Q with average y/y margin contraction of 10 bps.

Companies generally outperformed consensus on revenue and earnings in 2Q. Despite broader macro concerns heading into the 2Q earnings cycle this year, Business & Info Services companies generally outperformed consensus expectations, due to high quality business models in the sector and subdued expectations brought on by tariffs, which ultimately had limited impact in the quarter. Across our 27 company coverage universe that reported results, 23 companies surpassed consensus on revenue, 21 companies outperformed consensus on EBITDA margins and 20 companies beat consensus on EPS. The average upside vs consensus was \(1.6\%\) for revenue, 50 bps for EBITDA margins and \(4.5\%\) for EPS. We found that companies that outperformed the most on revenue had subdued expectations such as CLVT and strong pricing power such as FICO, which also drove upside at TRU. In contrast, companies facing cyclical or execution issues saw the most revenue underperformance relative to consensus estimates, such as BV and KLC.

Companies reported a mixture of positive and negative trends in the quarter, with many citing Al concerns and ongoing uncertainty in the macro environment, balanced by internal initiatives to drive outperformance. Below, we identify a number of key themes that emerged from the 2Q earnings cycle within Business & Info Services.

Gen Al's diverging impact across Business Services. Gartner's decelerating CV growth in 2Q and overall miss- and- cut results sparked a broader debate in Business Services on which companies are Gen Al winners and losers. Many investors are concerned that Gartner's research and insights can be replaced by LLMs. Those concerns spread to other companies in Business Services such as CSGP, FDS and several European Business Services names including RELGB and WKLNL. Ultimately, we believe having proprietary data generated in- house is one of the best sustainable moats for Info Services companies in the face of potential competition from Gen Al. Companies that we believe will be disrupted by Gen Al include staffers RHl and MAN that face threats not only from a decline in lower tier white collar staffing volumes but also from Gen Al native competitors that may be able to match employers and job candidates better than labor- based recruiters. Gen Al also represents a risk for HRB, in our view, since DIY competitors leveraging LLMs to offer tax support and insights reduces the value proposition of human- assisted tax prep services, and note the tax code is publicly available for free to train LLMs and taxes by design are rote and procedural. In contrast, SPGI, MCO, TRI and VRSK should benefit from Gen Al as agentic workflows can automate multi- step tasks such as credit memo generation and SwOT analysis, reducing tasks that take days to hours. These companies also have proprietary data, are embedded into existing workflows and have brand authority that serve as sustainable competitive moats.

Ongoing focus on macro sensitivity. We and investors continued to be focused on companies' macro sensitivity in the 2Q earnings cycle given ongoing tariff and geopolitical uncertainty. Companies with defensive qualities, such as ADT, BCO, BFAM, CTAS, FICO, IRM, ROL, ULS and VRSK, delivered healthy and predictable revenue results in 2Q. These companies benefited from pricing power, recurring revenue streams and/or a defensive end- market. Those with more cyclical exposures, including the rating agencies, financial data providers, consumer credit bureaus and staffers, had a broader range of outcomes, depending on the specific end market. Aside from staffing, cyclical companies in the sector overall surprised to the upside in 2Q on revenue and earnings relative to our estimates and FactSet consensus. Most cyclical companies also reaffirmed or raised their full- year guide. GS economists forecast real GDP to grow \(1.7\%\) in 2025 with a \(30\%\) recession probability, improved from \(1.0\%\) real GDP growth and a \(35\%\) recession probability three months earlier.

Limited direct negative tariff impact. Info Services companies generally faced limited tariff implications in 2Q given they sell data rather than physical goods. That said, Gartner cited negative trends in tariff- affected industries, which represent \(35 - 40\%\) of its total CV. Business Services companies also generally provide a

service rather than sell physical goods, though some companies are seeing rising costs from sourcing inventory. BV is experiencing project delays, in part, as subcontractors coming before BV face difficulties in material procurement caused by uncertain tariff policies. Similarly, NATL cited tariff exposure to ATM hardware produced overseas and imported into the US, with \(90\%\) imported from India, though the company has contingency plans to move production to Europe and Mexico. VSTS stopped providing quarterly guidance (after withdrawing annual guidance last quarter), citing uncertainty around the macro environment and the potential impact of tariffs on client purchasing behavior and input costs, lowering near- term visibility into financial performance. Interestingly, BCO benefited from a volatile global trade policy environment that drove increased movement of precious metals for hedging purposes.

US Dollar depreciation a significant tailwind in 2Q. Depreciation of the US Dollar in response to tariff policies represented a meaningful tailwind for many companies in the sector with non- US revenue exposures, contributing to revenue outperformance in 2Q and in some cases an increase to the full- year guide. Over the course of 2Q, the USD depreciated \(\sim 5\%\) against major currencies including the EUR, GBP, CAD and JPY. Companies in Business & Info Services with the largest non- US revenue mix include MAN, BCO, MSCI, ULS, NATL, KFY and CLVT at over \(50\%\) total revenue mix. Several companies notably raised their full- year guidance due to FX trends, including BFAM, EFX and IRM, while IT cited FX improvements as a mitigating factor for the revenue guide not being reduced more.

Debt issuance declined in 2Q but 2H performance should improve. Debt issuance declined in 2Q due to weak bank loan and structured finance activity, partially offset by growth in investment grade and high yield. A key driver of ratings revenue upside at SPGI and MCO in 2Q was private credit, which accounted for \(\sim 25\%\) of first- time issuance mandates at MCO, with the number of private credit deals up \(50\%\) y/y and private credit revenue up \(75\%\) , albeit off of a relatively low base. Private credit issuance is supporting AI data center investments, transition finance and energy infrastructure. Ratings revenue increased \(1\%\) y/y in 2Q at SPGI and was flat at MCO, moderating from high- single- digit growth in 1Q. Both companies increased their full- year outlook for ratings revenue, with SPGI now expecting \(2 - 5\%\) growth in Ratings revenue compared to \(0 - 4\%\) prior and MCO now expecting low- to- mid single- digits MIS revenue growth compared to flat- to- mid single- digits prior. Guidance assumes an inflection from debt issuance decline in 2Q to positive growth in the second half of the year driven by improving M&A volumes, a potential pull- forward of debt refinancing activity, lower interest rates and increased macro visibility.

Mixed buy- side and sell- side budget environment. Performance was mixed among companies serving buy- side and sell- side clients. SPGI's MI delivered healthy \(7\%\) y/y organic revenue growth in 2Q, accelerating from \(5\%\) in 1Q, driven by a revamped commercial structure and simplified sales incentives, resulting in a 1 ppt increase in net renewal rates and better win rates. SPGI expects MI growth to benefit in the second half of the year from lapping cancellations, and an upswing in sales and net renewals, with the broader external customer environment remaining

stable. Meanwhile, MCO's MA ARR growth remained strong at \(8\%\) y/y in 2Q though decelerated slightly from \(9\%\) in 1Q. MCO expects continued high- single- digit ARR growth over the remainder of 2025 supported by a strong and building pipeline that is heavily weighted in the back- half. In contrast, MSCI's active asset manager clients faced headwinds from fund outflows, cost pressures and consolidation, culminating in a deceleration in subscription run rate growth to \(6\%\) y/y in 2Q from \(8\%\) in 1Q and historical levels in the low- double- digits. This was partially mitigated by healthy growth from hedge funds, asset owners, VC/PE firms and wealth managers. FDS is also seeing budget pressures and vendor consolidation among traditional asset managers given an uncertain macro and market environment, as well as challenges from fee compression and the shift to passive asset management.

Consumer credit trends solid. US consumer credit trends exhibited solid performance despite an uncertain macro backdrop, supported by low unemployment, real wage gains and stable credit delinquencies. The credit bureaus indicated that lending volumes have remained stable at late- 2023/2024 levels with no signs of deterioration in 2Q or 3Q to- date. Credit origination volumes in non- mortgage categories were up roughly low- to- mid single- digits in the quarter. Due to strong price realization at FICO, the broader credit bureau ecosystem experienced a lift in mortgage revenue despite depressed mortgage volumes. FICO's Scores mortgage origination revenue grew a significant \(53\%\) y/y in F3Q and meaningfully outperformed the \(\sim 9\%\) drop in industry mortgage origination volumes. TRU expect mortgage volumes to be down modestly and EFX expects mortgage volumes to be down over \(11\%\) in 2025.

Federal government exposures had mixed impact. US federal government exposures had mixed impact on Business & Info Services companies in 2Q. IRM is currently awaiting news on a potential 5- year contract with the US Department of Treasury to assist in digitization efforts that could drive a step- up in digital solutions revenue growth. EFX should also benefit from the One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA), signed into law on 7/4/25, which will increase the frequency of CMS redeterminations from annual to semi- annual, add work requirements for certain Medicaid recipients and tie federal funding to error rates, leading to more frequent income verification checks by government agencies in 2026. In contrast, Gartner saw just a \(47\%\) renewal rate for the \(60\%\) of US federal contracts coming up for renewal in the first half, which stepped down from a \(50\%\) renewal rate for \(40\%\) of US federal contracts up for renewal in 1Q, primarily causing Insight (formerly Research) CV growth to decelerate from \(6.7\%\) y/y in 1Q to \(4.9\%\) in 2Q. CLVT and MH also have indirect exposures to reductions in federal spending on higher education, though this has not materialized in their 2Q results.

Temp staffing in decline, with no positive inflection in volumes. Temp staffing trends remained challenged in 2Q, with no positive inflection in volumes observed. RHl's temp staffing revenue decreased \(11\%\) y/y in 2Q and \(10\%\) in the first two weeks of July as macro uncertainty is dampening business confidence and causing clients to exercise caution in hiring, and 3Q guidance points to a similar low- to- mid teens decline. Meanwhile, MAN's revenue fell \(4\%\) y/y on a CC basis in 2Q due to reduced staffing demand in Europe and North America, with particularly weak trends

in Northern Europe, and management is guiding to \(2\%\) CC decline at the midpoint in 3Q. Outside of the temp staffing space, KFY is seeing improved labor market trends, albeit off of depressed levels, in most of its cyclically sensitive businesses, with overall new business ex RPO accelerating from \(1\%\) y/y CC growth in F3Q 2025 to \(5\%\) in F4Q. Despite macro uncertainty, Korn Ferry overall is benefiting from broader labor market trends such as an aging workforce, client organizational complexity and a push for efficiency.

Pricing increases a key tailwind for revenue growth. A number of companies continued to enjoy strong pricing power, with some raising prices well in excess of inflation. ROL achieved healthy pricing increases of \(3 - 4\%\) in 2Q, improved from \(1 - 2\%\) pre- COVID, to better reflect the value of services provided. IRM's revenue management strategy, which since COVID has produced pricing increases well ahead of inflation in a relatively price- inelastic market to match the value of services provided, yielded pricing gains of mid- to- high single- digits in 2Q. Notably, FICO continues to enact special pricing increases in its Scores business to make up for decades of no pricing increases, with mortgage score pricing increases of \(40\% +\) and accelerating auto score pricing increases of \(10\% +\) in F3Q.

Subscription revenues prove resilient. Despite heightened economic uncertainty in 2Q, subscription revenue streams remained highly resilient. Subscription revenues at CSGP, CTAS, IRM, FICO, MCO, MSCI, ROL, SPGI, TRI and VRSK realized solid and largely consistent or improving y/y growth in 2Q. Retention rates were stable and strong across the vast majority of these names, though new business trends were more mixed. For example, new business trends at CSGP improved q/q but stayed muted at MSCI in 2Q.

Full- year guidance mostly reaffirmed with 2Q results. During the 2Q earnings cycle, companies for the most part reaffirmed their full- year guidance, despite the outperformance in the quarter, to account for ongoing macro uncertainty. Of the companies that changed their full- year outlook, more companies raised their guide than lowered it, reflecting the flow- through of outperformance in the quarter or FX. With respect to revenue, 10 companies reaffirmed their full- year guide (ADT, BV, BCO, CLVT, FDS, FICO, MCO, NATL, TRI, ULS), 7 companies raised their full- year guide (BFAM, CSGP, EFX, IRM, SPGI, TRU, VRSK) and 2 companies lowered their full- year guide (IT, KLC) – out of those that provide full- year guidance. The revenue guidance cut at IT was due to reduced federal government spending and tariff headwinds, and at KLC was due to lower occupancy rates. Companies that raised their full- year revenue guidance increased it by an average of 90 bps, while those that cut their full- year guide reduced it by an average of 110 bps. With respect to EBITDA margins, 14 companies reaffirmed their full- year guide (ADT, BV, BCO, CLVT, FDS, IT, IRM, KLC, MCO, SPGI, TRI, TRU, ULS, VRSK), 1 company raised its full- year guide by 30 bps (CSGP) and 1 company trimmed its full- year guide by 20 bps (EFX) – out of those that provided full- year guidance. The EBITDA margin guidance cut was related to increased consumer litigation costs at EFX.

With respect to EPS, 3 companies reaffirmed their full-year guide (CLVT, FDS, NATL), 9 companies raised their full-year guide (ADT, BFAM, EFX, FICO, IT, IRM, MCO, SPGI, TRU) and 2 companies reduced their full-year guide (KLC, VRSK) – out of those that provided full-year guidance. Companies that raised their full-year EPS guidance increased it by an average of 190 bps, while those that cut their full-year guide reduced it by an average of 70 bps.

GS estimates raised for revenue, lowered for margin and EPS. Coming out of the 2Q earnings cycle, we raised our CY2025 estimates for revenue and lowered our estimates for EBITDA margins and EPS, with an average increase to our revenue estimates of \(0.1\%\) and an average decrease of 10 bps for EBITDA margins and \(2.5\%\) for EPS. Our revenue outlook for CY2025 was strengthened the most at companies benefiting from strong ratings revenue (MCO, SPGI), organic turnaround progress (CLVT) or FX (IRM, MAN). Conversely, our revenue estimates for the year were reduced the most at companies seeing reduced customer spending or timing delays (BV, IT, KLC) or staffing headwinds (KFY, RHI). Meanwhile, our EBITDA margin estimates for CY2025 were raised the most at companies with additional cost efficiencies, operating leverage or pricing flow- through (BFAM, BV, FICO). On the other hand, our EBITDA margin outlook for the year was reduced the most at companies experiencing less operating leverage revenue (IT, RHI), increased investment spend (CTAS), revenue mix (CLVT) or elevated operating expenses (HRB, ROL).

Consensus estimates for CY2025 were increased for revenue, stable for EBITDA margins and reduced for EPS following the 2Q earnings cycle, with an average increase of \(0.5\%\) in revenue growth and an average decrease of \(1.2\%\) in EPS. There were 11 companies with the distinction of seeing upward full- year consensus estimate revisions for revenue, EBITDA margins and EPS: BCO, BFAM, CTAS, FDS, IRM, KFY, MSCI, NATL, SPGI, TRI, TRU). In contrast, companies that saw negative full- year consensus estimate revisions across revenue, EBITDA margins and EPS included EFX, FICO, IT, KLC, RHI and VSTS. On average, CY2025 consensus revenue growth improved from \(4.1\%\) pre- earnings to \(4.5\%\) post- earnings primarily due to outperformance in the quarter and FX tailwinds, consensus EBITDA margin expansion remained consistent at 50 bps, and consensus EPS growth narrowed from \(12.8\%\) pre- earnings to \(12.0\%\) post- earnings.

The company is also passing through accelerated double- digit auto score pricing increases that we believe can be sustained over time. Despite the FHFAs recent lender choice announcement for mortgage scores, FICO expects lenders to continue to rely on Classic FICO and, increasingly, FICO 10T scores, with no lenders switching to VantageScore since the FHFAs decision, and importantly noted that its original mortgage score pricing strategy has not changed. The company is also delivering accelerating Software platform ARR growth in the high- teens, with a path to return to \(\sim 30\%\) growth over the long term. We believe FICO can continue to deliver mid- teens revenue growth and \(20\% +\) EPS growth supported by the company's ongoing ability to close the price- to- value gap in its Scores business and idiosyncratic platform transformation in its Software business. The sell- off in FICO shares following FHFA developments presents an attractive buying opportunity, particularly given the company's economics remain intact, in our view.

Gartner (IT, Buy- rated, \(457 12M PT,\) 19bn market cap): Gartner is experiencing headwinds from the US federal government, tariffs and elongated sales cycles in its Insights segment, culminating in a deceleration in contract value (CV) growth to \(5\%\) in 2Q from \(7\%\) in 1Q, with management expecting CV growth to further decelerate to low- to- mid single- digits by year- end 2025 based on a continuation of 2Q trends. The company laid out catalysts for a reacceleration in CV growth to high- single- digits by the end of 2026 and double- digits over the medium term, including the lapping of federal contract headwinds, a normalization of spending by tariff- impacted companies, recovering tech vendor growth, and improving internal operations around products and sales. We believe Gartner is under- earning as result of transient headwinds, and that these catalysts will drive reacceleration in CV growth in 2026, with no change in the company's long- term growth algorithm. We also believe that concerns AI will disintermediate Gartner's research have no basis, given that the company's insights and analyses are proprietary and cannot replicated by LLMs, and that research obtained from AI would be inferior to Gartner's research and potentially dated or misleading.

Iron Mountain (IRM, Buy- rated, \(122 12M PT,\) 27bn market cap): Iron Mountain is generating robust organic revenue growth, which accelerated to \(9\%\) y/y in 2Q from \(8\%\) in 1Q, supported by pricing power in its legacy records information management business and positive trends in the growth portfolio composed of its data center, asset lifecycle management (ALM) and digital solutions businesses. Revenue management continues to drive mid- to- high single- digit pricing growth in the legacy records information management business, with stable volumes, and the growth portfolio is collectively growing \(20\% +\) organically and approaching \(30\%\) of total revenue. Within this growth portfolio, data center revenue growth is accelerating, registering \(26\%\) y/y in 2Q vs \(21\%\) in 1Q, and is tracking to reach nearly \(30\%\) growth by year- end 2025 and sustain \(25\% +\) growth in 2026 driven by data center commencements. While new data center signings slowed in 1H due to hyperscaler focus on LLM campuses, customer attention is now shifting back to inference and cloud infrastructure, which is IRM's core market and should drive a rebound in new signings. We believe IRM's healthy organic revenue growth is sustainable, and capable of driving double- digit AFFO/shr growth accompanied by valuation upside in the shares.

S&P Global (SPGI, Buy-rated, \(\) 630\(12M PT,\) \ \(169bn\) market cap): S&P delivered modestly positive growth in Ratings in 2Q that surprised to the upside against a backdrop of lower billed debt issuance, lifted by growth in non- transaction revenue, private credit, and investment grade and high yield issuance activity. Meanwhile, SPGI's non- Ratings businesses, which comprise \(70\%\) of total revenue, are collectively generating strong high- single- digit revenue growth, led by mid- teens growth in Indices. Notably, the company is making progress with its revenue transformation in Market Intelligence driven by a revamped commercial structure and simplified sales incentives, with revenue growth tracking to accelerate in the second half of the year from an upswing in sales and net renewals, as well as lapping cancellations. We believe ongoing Ratings revenue upside potential, improving growth in Market Intelligence, strong Indices growth and ramping AI initiatives serve as drivers of upside in SPGI shares. SPGI is also making progress with its Mobility spin- off, with operations being carved out and new leadership appointed.

ADT (ADT, Buy- rated, \(\) 10.40\(12M PT,\) \ \(7bn\) market cap): ADT is delivering resilient and accelerated revenue growth despite macro uncertainty, reflecting the defensiveness of its business model. Gross recurring monthly revenue additions in the quarter benefited from a bulk account purchase completed at favorable economics, while average pricing continues to rise on greater consumer adoption of the ADT+ platform, household device penetration and outright installation sales. The company is notably investing in AI to fuel customer service, sales and back- office efficiencies, which we expect to catalyze stronger revenue and margin performance over the medium term. Notably, ADT is tracking to grow FCF mid- teens this year, following strong \(42\%\) FCF growth in 2024, reflecting disciplined subscriber acquisition spend, which we believe will drive upside in the shares.

Bright Horizons (BFAM, Buy- rated, \(\) 146\(12M PT,\) \ \(7bn\) market cap): Bright Horizons is making progress with driving a recovery in full service child care center occupancy rates, which reached high- 60s in 2Q, up from mid- 60s in the year- ago period compared to pre- COVID levels in the \(70\% +\) range. The company is pruning underperforming centers with low occupancy rates, and undertaking initiates to streamline the conversion of inquiries to enrollments. BFAM also has had a good start to the important Fall enrollment season with enrollments tracking to sustain low- single- digit growth seen in 2Q over the remainder of this year, supported by good lead generation and stepped up targeted outreach. Back- up care once again delivered robust double- digit growth on higher utilization rates. We believe ongoing improvements in center occupancy rates toward pre- COVID levels will drive attractive incremental margins, strong double- digit EPS growth and valuation upside.

BrightView (BV, Sell- rated, \(\) 13.50\(12M PT,\) \ \(2bn\) market cap): BrightView's revenue continues to be in a broad- based decline seen since early F2024, widening from down \(1.5\%\) y/y in F2Q to down \(4.1\%\) in F3Q due to reduced discretionary customer spend in the landscape maintenance business and project delays in the development business.

Discretionary spending cuts in landscape maintenance are due to macro and budget headwinds, and are weighing on demand for ancillary services and, to a lesser extent, contracted services where customers are requesting fewer service occurrences to manage costs. Meanwhile, development delays are stemming from labor and material shortages at subcontractors coming before BV due to immigration and tariff policies. We see downside in BV shares driven by negative estimate revisions to reflect customer budget headwinds and project delays, which add to existing challenges associated with operating in a competitive industry with limited pricing power and difficulty in balancing strong growth with margin expansion.

Brink's (BCO, Buy- rated, \(119 12M PT,\) 5bn market cap): Brink's is sustaining stable mid- single- digit organic revenue growth, in line with its medium- term growth target, led by mid- to- high teens growth in Digital Retail Solutions (DRS) and ATM Managed Services (AMS), which comprise \(\sim 25\%\) of total revenue. The company is seeing positive momentum in its DRS/AMS offerings that should drive an acceleration in growth in the second half of the year lifted by a strong pipeline, accelerating conversions from cash & valuables management to DRS and large AMS wins. The company is also tracking to expand its EBITDA margins 30- 50 bps on a full- year basis to \(18.5 - 18.7\%\) , approaching its medium- term target of \(20\%\) , with y/y margin expansion stepping up in 2H compared to 1H driven by revenue mix, productivity gains, operating leverage and easy expense comps. We believe further traction with DRS/AMS offerings and strengthening margins will drive upside in BCO shares.

Clarivate (CLVT, Buy- rated, \(4.80 12M PT,\) 3bn market cap): Clarivate is making incremental progress in driving a turnaround in organic revenue growth, which accelerated fractionally from \(0.3\%\) y/y in 1Q to \(0.5\%\) in 2Q. The improved growth performance is being driven by execution of the company's Value Creation Plan, which involves increasing the mix of recurring revenues, driving stronger sales execution, innovating on products with an emphasis on AI and conducting portfolio rationalization actions. CLVT now expects recurring revenue, comprising \(88\%\) of total revenue in 1H, to land in the upper half of its reaffirmed guidance range of \((1) - 1\%\) in 2025 due to improving momentum with renewal rates and new business wins. Disposals of non- core assets such as ProQuest e- Books are tracking slightly lower than management initially expected, which will help reported revenue but negatively impact margins for the full year. Representing partial offsets, transactional revenue continues to be decline, which admittedly is part of CLVT's strategy to shift to subscription revenue, and no update was provided on the company's strategic review on potential asset sales. We believe CLVT's idiosyncratic turnaround strategic and discounted valuation present an attractive risk- reward profile.

CoStar (CSGP, Buy- rated, \(105 12M PT,\) 38bn market cap): CoStar delivered a significant step- up in net bookings to \(93mm in 2Q, up 65\% q/q and 39\% y/y, with Apartments.com bookings increasing q/q to\) 45mn from \(25mn and Homes.com bookings rising q/q to\) 12mn from \((\) 4mn). Bookings trends are being lifted by significant sales force expansion across the commercial and residential businesses, with stronger sales productivity. Homes.com is notably gaining traction, with the full- year guide for residential revenue raised, helped by lower pricing to drive greater market

penetration while maintaining strong profitability. The company remains on track to complete its acquisition of Domain in Australia for \(\) 1.5bn\(in 3Q. We believe positive bookings trends support accelerating organic revenue growth, which combined with significant margin expansion and upward estimate revisions should drive valuation upside in the shares.

Equifax (EFX, Neutral- rated, \(\) 253\(12M PT,\) \ \(31bn\) market cap): Equifax is continuing to see a stable lending environment despite macro uncertainty, with B2B non- mortgage revenue up \(4\%\) y/y in 2Q, albeit at levels below historical norms. Mortgage revenue also increased a robust \(20\%\) y/y in the quarter, driving the majority of the revenue upside, reflecting strength from pricing flow- through from FICO and mortgage pre- approval & pre- qualification solutions, the latter of which should benefit in 2H from integration with the TWN indicator product at no additional cost to customers. That said, we expect EWS revenue performance in the second half of the year to be dampened by funding pressures among state agencies given reduced federal reimbursements, weak talent solutions and employer services trends in the context of soft white collar hiring volumes, and recent share loss in criminal background screening. We also have a more conservative EBITDA margin outlook due to higher litigation expenses, and now expect flat margins on a full- year basis.

FactSet (FDS, Sell- rated, \(\) 412\(12M PT,\) \ \(15bn\) market cap): FactSet is seeing largely stable external customer trends, with positive ASV performance among wealth, dealmaker, PE/VC and hedge fund clients, mitigated by softness among traditional asset managers. Organic ASV growth is tracking to be \(\sim 5\%\) for F2025, with a solid pipeline leading up to the seasonally strong F4Q, though this growth represents essentially no acceleration from F2024's ASV growth of \(5.1\%\) despite easy comps from the UBS/CS merger, and revenue growth for the year is guided to decelerate to \(\sim 5\%\) from \(5.7\%\) in F2024. Price realization remains a challenge as international pricing increases in F3Q were just \(1\%\) , moderating from \(2\%\) in the year- ago period on disinflation and required discounting to win and maintain business. Of note, EBITDA margins declined meaningfully y/y in F3Q and are tracking to fall again in F4Q due to increased compensation and product development expenses, highlighting the difficulties in delivering both accelerating ASV growth and margin expansion simultaneously in a highly competitive market.

H&R Block (HRB, Sell- rated, \(\) 48\(12M PT,\) \ \(7bn\) market cap): H&R Block closed out the 2025 tax season with F2025 revenue growth in both assisted and DIY driven by pricing and complexity mix, with volumes down in both categories. EBITDA came below the midpoint of the guide for the year due to elevated operating expenses, while EPS missed due to delayed tax benefits. For the 2026 tax season, HRB is assuming \(\sim 1\%\) industry volume growth with 20 bps of mix shift from DIY to assisted, similar to the 2025 tax season, though we believe the mix shift may be optimistic given consumer behaviors could normalize next year back to long- term historical trends. Importantly, management guided to ongoing volume market share losses in its core assisted category in F2026 at roughly half the rate as in F2025 at the midpoint, accompanied by additional share losses in free DIY albeit at a narrower rate. Despite recent positive trends in pricing and mix, we believe continued volume market share losses at HRB are

not sustainable over the long term. Further, we see a secular reversion in mix shift from assisted to DIY filings, competitive threats from TurboTax in both categories, and disintermediation risks from AI.

KinderCare (KLC, Buy- rated, \(20 12M PT,\) 1bn market cap): KinderCare is experiencing enrollment and occupancy headwinds, which management attributed to local market dynamics such as high teacher turnover and low conversion from inquiries to enrollments, rather than any single factor across its centers. Occupancy rates declined 130 bps y/y to \(71\%\) in 2Q, and management expects occupancy to contract 100- 150 bps for the full year. Incrementally, private pay families are also taking longer to enroll due to macro uncertainty. That said, we expect enrollments to return to positive growth over the next four quarters as the company applies a centralized data- driven diagnostic approach to address occupancy gaps at the local level, and as macro concerns ease. KLC's revenue outlook is also supported by positive federal funding dynamics, healthy Champions and B2B growth, and improving performance among its bottom quintile centers. We see strong incremental margins and EPS growth when enrollments recover, supporting valuation upside.

Korn Ferry (KFY, Buy- rated, \(85 12M PT,\) 4bn market cap): Despite macro uncertainty, Korn Ferry is delivering accelerating revenue growth and quarterly new business growth, reflecting strong execution in cross- selling and client wallet penetration. The company is also benefiting from favorable labor market trends including an aging workforce driving demand for executive search and rising organizational complexity driving demand for transformative consulting engagements. Executive search volumes rebounded sharply in F4Q, driving most of the revenue upside. KFY released its fourth edition of Talent Suite in F4Q, which should drive accelerated digital segment revenue growth in CY2026 and potential upside to management's \(16 - 18\%\) medium- term EBITDA margin target. We believe KFY's diversified revenue streams, effective cross- selling and share gains, leverage to secular labor market tailwinds and significant remaining fees under existing contracts will drive healthy valuation upside over the next 12 months.

Manpower (MAN, Sell- rated, \(39 12M PT,\) 2bn market cap): We believe Manpower continues to face an uncertain and volatile operating environment following 2Q results, which included a low- to- mid single- digit y/y CC revenue decline and margin contraction from negative operating leverage. Northern Europe remains the most challenged of MAN's geographies due to weak regional macro trends and geopolitical headwinds from the Russia- Ukraine war and the associated impact on energy prices. In light of ongoing weakness in Northern Europe, the company carried out further restructuring actions in the region across front- and- back office functions to rightsize the cost base. We acknowledge signs of stabilization in 2Q in the US and parts of Europe as tariff- related uncertainty eased, culminating in narrowing revenue declines that outperformed our estimates and consensus. That said, we see potential downside to estimates if tariff headwinds resurface, and view AI as a longer- term risk to coding and clerical temp staffing volumes at MAN.
Moody's (MCO, Neutral- rated, \(535 12M PT,\) 92bn market cap): Moody's ratings business is benefiting from mix tailwinds and contributions from private credit, which

enabled MIS revenue be flat y/y in 2Q, meaningfully better than rated debt issuance declines of \(12\%\) . The company raised its full- year outlook for rated debt issuance on the back of 2Q issuance outperformance, with positive mix and private credit strength likely to persist. The MA business is also delivering stable and healthy \(8\%\) y/y organic revenue growth, consistent with ARR growth trends throughout the year. MCO delivered strong EBITDA margin expansion of 130 bps y/y, as well, with expansion in both MIS and MA, driven by operating leverage and efficiencies. We believe MCO's favorable operating trends are balanced by a premium valuation relative to peers, and lingering debt issuance uncertainty over the remainder of the year.

MSCI (MSCI, Buy- rated, \(\) 634\(12M PT,\) \ \(44bn\) market cap): MSCI delivered healthy asset- based fee growth in the low- teens y/y in 2Q driven by a market recovery and a rotation of assets from the US into international markets, where the company has a strong presence. Non- active manager subscription run rate, comprising \(\sim 50\%\) of overall run rate, also delivered attractive \(11.5\%\) y/y growth in the quarter reflecting growing demand from banks & broker dealers, hedge funds, wealth managers and asset owners for MSCI's portfolio and risk solutions. That said, active manager subscription run rate, representing the remaining \(50\%\) of overall run rate, continued to face challenges from fund outflows, cost pressures and consolidation that resulted in just \(6\%\) y/y growth in 2Q. While MSCI noted that active manager subscription trends will remain subdued over the near term, we believe subscription organic revenue growth will nonetheless improve by 4Q based on net new recurring subscription sales trends to- date.

NCR Atleos (NATL, Neutral- rated, \(\) 34\(12M PT,\) \ \(3bn\) market cap): NCR Atleos is effectively executing on its ATMaaS strategy to bundle software and services, and occasionally hardware, together into a comprehensive solution for ATM management. ATMaaS revenue increased a strong \(32\%\) y/y in 2Q and the company expects growth to accelerate to \(40\% +\) in 3Q/4Q driven by growth in unique customers and a favorable mix shift to high- ARPU regions such as North America. NATL's SSB segment additionally benefited from consistent growth in broader software and services and a jump in hardware sales partly related to a shift in order timing from 1Q to 2Q. The company's SSB segment is also seeing healthy margin expansion from growth in high- margin products such as ATMaaS and productivity initiatives. That said, hardware strength in 2Q related to timing will likely normalize in 2H and the company's Network business continues to have subdued revenue trends due to declining cash withdrawal transaction volumes.

Robert Half (RHI, Sell- rated, \(\) 34\(12M PT,\) \ \(4bn\) market cap): Elevated macro uncertainty is limiting hiring activity and new project starts for Robert Half, culminating in a \(7\%\) y/y revenue decline in 2Q that worsened from a \(6\%\) decline in 1Q. Revenue trends during 2Q were volatile, falling the first two months of the quarter before showing some signs of stabilization at lower levels in June and early July. The company expects overall revenue declines in 3Q on a same day CC basis to match 2Q at the midpoint, pointing to ongoing staffing headwinds. With sustained revenue declines, RHI is also experiencing operating margin contraction from negative operating leverage. Importantly, the negative estimate revision cycle at RHI is ongoing, with the guide for 3Q EPS coming nearly \(30\%\) below consensus. We believe lingering macro uncertainty,
negative earnings estimate revisions and medium- to- longer term risks from Al on white collar temp staffing volumes will drive further valuation downside in RHI shares.

Rollins (ROL, Buy- rated, \(\) 62\(12M PT,\) \ \(27bn market cap): Rollins' operating performance reflects the inherent resilience of its business model attributable to the non- cyclical and essential nature of pest control, as well as the company's idiosyncratic initiatives to drive growth. ROL is delivering robust organic revenue growth in the 7- 8% range, consistent with the company's growth outlook over the medium term, lifted by increased residential cross- selling activity, a sharper focus in commercial and broader share gains from competitors. M&A opportunities in a fragmented market add to the overall growth outlook, with ROL targeting 300- 400 bps of growth contribution from acquisitions this year. While EBITDA margins contracted y/y in the quarter due to developments on legacy auto claims, which are one- off in nature, underlying margins expanded driven by efficiencies in its procurement, technology and back- office functions. We believe ROL has attractive valuation upside potential given its strong and durable organic growth outlook, which we find particularly appealing in the current uncertain macro environment.

Thomson Reuters (TRI/TRI.TO, Neutral- rated, \(\) 192/C\(\) 266\(12M PT,\) \ \(79bn market cap): Thomson Reuters is delivering healthy organic revenue growth in the high- single- digit range in its Big 3 segments, with 9% y/y growth in 2Q that was consistent with 1Q. The company's full- year outlook suggests Big 3 organic revenue growth will remain strong at 9% y/y in the second half of the year, backed by new product innovations, particularly involving Al. Gen Al- enabled products now comprise 22% of total ACV, up from 20% in 1Q, and the company is pushing forward with new Al products across Legal and Tax & Accounting including CoCounsel Legal, Deep Research, Ready to Advise and new agent- guided legal workflows. We believe strong organic growth and margin performance in the quarter is balanced by lack of an increase to the full- year guide despite the 2Q beat, less margin expansion opportunity in 2H due to a push- out of planned expenses from 1H, and muted trends outside of the Big 3 segments, including tough comps in Reuters from a lapping one- time Gen Al licensing deal from 3Q 2024 and ongoing declines in Print.

TransUnion (TRU, Neutral- rated, \(\) 102\(12M PT,\) \ \(18bn market cap): TransUnion is seeing stable lending volumes and consumer financial health that outperformed management's expectations of deteriorating conditions. In 2Q, credit card volumes were flat y/y, auto loan volumes were up low- single- digits lifted by April tariff- related pull- forward purchase activity and consumer lending volumes were up mid- teens. Mortgage credit inquiries were also flat y/y, though mortgage revenue representing 12% of LTM revenue rose a robust 29% on FICO pricing increases. The company now expects full- year organic constant currency revenue growth of 6- 7%, up from 4.5- 6% previously, and noted that a continuation of July credit trends could land revenue at or above the upper end of the guidance range. We believe TRU's results were clean in 2Q, in contrast to EFX, where the EWS business faced headwinds from state budgets, white collar hiring volumes and share shifts in criminal background screening. That said, TRU's margin outlook for in the back half of the year is challenged, with EBITDA margins contracting 40 bps y/y in 3Q and 120 bps in 4Q based on guidance due to M&A margin
dilution, investment activity, fewer productivity benefits and revenue mix.

UL Solutions (ULS, Neutral- rated, \(\) 69\(12M PT,\) \ \(139\) bn market cap): UL Solutions is generally seeing resilient customer demand and ongoing new product development needs that require certification, with tariffs serving as a potential positive catalyst if they lead to product redesigns or geographic shifts in manufacturing. Industrial organic growth in 2Q was healthy at \(7\%\) lifted by energy and automation testing needs, with future growth supported by expanding battery lab testing capacity in the US and EU, and new testing services for immersion cooling fluids leveraged to Al- driven infrastructure build- out. That said, ULS' reaffirmed full- year organic growth outlook of mid- single- digits implies no reacceleration in growth in the second half of the year from 2Q levels of \(\sim 5.5\%\) , with comps notably difficult in the Industrial segment in 4Q due to a pull- forward of activity into 4Q 2024, and advisory revenue in decline due to sustainability regulation shifts and soft CRE market in the US. EBITDA margin expansion y/y is also tracking to slow meaningfully in 2H due to less operating leverage and tougher comps.

Verisk (VRSK, Neutral- rated, \(\) 315\(12M PT,\) \ \(38bn market cap\) : Verisk is delivering healthy subscription organic CC revenue growth in the high- single- digits, though growth decelerated from low- double- digits in 1Q. The company completed its acquisition of SuranecBay for \(\) 163\(mn on 7/17 and announced its pending acquisition of AccuLynx for\) \ \(2.35bn\) that management expects to close in 3Q, which the company indicated drove the increase to its full- year revenue guide. VRSK is also generating robust EBITDA margin expansion from operating leverage and cost efficiencies. That said, we expect subscription OCC revenue growth to continue to moderate in the second half of the year to the mid- single- digits due to a normalization of attrition to historical levels, as well as potential headwinds from reduced federal government spending, competitive pressures in the auto segment and reduced insurer discretionary spend in states such as CA. The company noted that its 2025 EPS outlook is also coming down, due to anticipated dilution from debt to finance the pending AccuLynx deal. We believe the company's fundamentals are fairly reflected in its premium valuation multiple.

Vestis (VSTS, Neutral- rated, \(\) 6.10\(12M PT,\) \ \(0.6bn market cap\) : Vestis' revenue remains in contraction territory, though narrowed in the rate of decline to \(3\%\) y/y in F3Q from \(6\%\) in F2Q. Overall churn was not offset by business from new customers, and the penetration of existing customers decreased. The company under new management is looking to implement value- based pricing, improve service quality, increase sales force effectiveness and optimize its cost of service. We believe VSTS is on a multi- quarter journey to implement these initiatives that should improve pricing, retention, new business and margin trends, and view execution risk and limited near- term revenue visibility as fairly reflected in the company's discounted valuation multiple.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
